uanced reframing and reassessment of the economic, institutional, and intellectual history of the managerial era.Langlois argues that managerialism rose to prominence not because of its inherent superiority but because of its contingent value in a young and rapidly developing American economy. The structures of managerialism solidified their dominance only because the century’s great catastrophes of war, depression, and war again superseded markets, scrambled relative prices, and weakened market-supporting institutions. By the end of the twentieth century, Langlois writes, these market-supporting institutions had reemerged to shift advantage toward entrepreneurial and market-driven modes of organization.This magisterial new account of the rise and fall of managerialism holds significant implications for contemporary debates about industrial and antitrust policies and the role of the corporation in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAntitrust law-United States. 0aBusiness enterprises-United States-History-20th century. 0aBusiness planning-United States. 0aCorporations-United States-History-20th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Corporate & Business History.2bisacsh  aAnschluss.  aBessemer process.  aCapitalism.  aClayton Antitrust Act.  aCompetition law.  aCompetition.  aConsumer.  aCorporate group.  aCustomer.  aDeregulation.  aDiversification (marketing strategy).  aDrexel Burnham Lambert.  aDuPont.  aEconomics.  aEconomist.  aEconomy.  aEmployment.  aFederal Reserve Note.  aFederal Trade Commission.  aFinance.  aGeneral Motors.  aHepburn Act.  aHerbert Hoover.  aIBM.  aIG Farben.  aIncome.  aInflation.  aJohn Maynard Keynes.  aJoseph Schumpeter.  aKeynesian economics.  aLehman Brothers.  aManufacturing.  aMass production.